First convert the observed line energy to a frequency to identify the transition. 1. Energy–frequency relation: \( E = h
u \) ⇒ \( 
u = \dfrac{E}{h} \) 2. Convert 3.9 μeV to Hz using \( h = 4.136	imes10^{-15} \,	ext{eV·s} \): \[ 
u =  rac{3.9	imes10^{-6}\,	ext{eV}}{4.136	imes10^{-15}\,	ext{eV·s}} \approx 9.4	imes10^8\,	ext{Hz} = 943\,	ext{MHz} \] Corresponding wavelength: \[ \lambda =  rac{c}{
u} \approx  rac{3	imes10^8\,	ext{m/s}}{9.4	imes10^8\,	ext{Hz}} \approx 0.32\,	ext{m} \approx 32\,	ext{cm} \] 3. Compare with known interstellar lines: - HI 21-cm line: ν ≈ 1420 MHz, E ≈ 5.9 μeV. - Our observed line at 943 MHz is lower by a factor ≈ 1420/943 ≈ 1.5, consistent with a redshifted 21-cm line at z ≈ 0.5: \[ 1+z =  rac{
u_{	ext{rest}}}{
u_{	ext{obs}}} \approx  rac{1420}{943} \approx 1.5 \Rightarrow z \approx 0.5 \] A comoving distance of ~2.1 Gpc is consistent with such a redshift. So this absorption feature is almost certainly the redshifted 21-cm hyperfine transition of neutral...
